from gene replacement of mouse apoe with human APOE*2. J Clin Invest, 102(1):130-5. Origin: The APOE2 targeted 
replacement mouse was developed in the laboratory of Nobuya Maeda at the
 University of North Carolina. The model was created by targeting the 
murine Apoe gene for replacement with the human APOE2 allele in E14TG2a 
ES cells and injecting the targeted cells into blastocysts. Resultant 
chimeras were backcrossed to C57BL/6 for seven generations (N7). Taconic

(N9) and embryo transfer derived. The colony is maintained through 
incrossing of homozygotes.

strain_set.creator: person:4
strain_set.name: RUB331
strain_set.notes: First, it may be that you will see improved growth if you supplement LB with thymine at 20 ug/ml. Second, please keep in mind that this strain is blocked at the earliest stage of sporulation and will eventually lyse on the plate. It is important to subculture the strain soon after it arrives. Finally, cultures should be kept at room temperature and never stored under refrigeration. B. subtilis RUB331 is definitely not wild-type.  It was created by transforming DNA (total gDNA?) from wt (B. subtilis 168T.sup.+) into RUB830.  It's unclear where RUB830 originated.  Earliest reference to "RUB 330" that I can find is from 1976 (https://jvi.asm.orgasbin/content/jvi/21/2/522.full.pdf).  ATCC lists RUB331 as a "transformation host", but I only find a limited number of papers that reference it, perhaps because it was patented.
strain_set.summary: Sporulation is blocked at an early stage, so the colonies will eventually lyse and die.  Do not recommend storing agar plates under refrigeration.  Strictly requires thymine and tryptophan in minimal media.
